<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-sequences" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Sequences</title>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-sequences-definitions">
    <title>Definitions</title>

    <p>
      An <term>infinite sequence</term><idx><h>sequence</h></idx> is a
      function whose domain is the ordered set <m>(\N, \le)</m>. In this
      chapter we only consider sequences of real numbers, so we simply
      call them sequences. If <m>\vx</m> is a sequence, we write <m>x_n</m>
      for its value at <m>n</m> and call <m>x_n</m> the <term><m>n</m>-th
      term</term><idx><h>term</h><h>of a sequence</h></idx> of <m>\vx</m>. We
      also denote the sequence <m>\vx</m> by <m>(x_n)</m>, and we identify
      a real number <m>r</m> with the constant sequence <m>n \mapsto r</m>.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-basic-sequences">
      <statement>
      <p>Since sequences are in particular real-valued functions, adjectives
      for real-valued functions apply to them as well:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><m>(1/n)</m> is decreasing and bounded.</li>

	  <li><m>(n)</m> is increasing and bounded below, but not bounded above.</li>
          
	  <li><m>((-1)^n)</m> is bounded, but neither increasing nor decreasing.</li>
        </ul>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      A sequence <m>\vx</m> is <term>null</term><idx>null sequence</idx>
      if for every <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> there exists <m>N \in \N</m>
      such that <me>
        |x_n| \lt \varepsilon \quad\text{for all } n \ge N.
      </me> 

      In words, a sequence <m>\vx = (x_n)</m> is null if the absolute value
      of its terms <m>|x_n|</m> can be arbitrarily close to zero provided
      that the index <m>n</m> of the terms is sufficiently large.
    </p>

    <p>
      It often makes an argument more intuitive by replacing "there exists <m>N
      \in \N</m> such that for all <m>n \ge N</m>" with either of the
      following phrases:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>for all sufficiently large <m>n</m>,</li>
      <li>for all but finitely many <m>n</m>.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      We may abbreviate "<m>n</m> is sufficiently large" by <m>n \gg 0</m> or
      <m>n \approx \infty</m>. For example, the statement <m>\vx \approx 0</m>
      means that for every <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>, we have
      <m>|x_n| \lt \varepsilon</m> for all <m>n \gg 0</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      We say that a sequence <m>\vx</m> <term>converges</term><idx>convergent
      sequence</idx> to <m>r \in\R</m> or <m>r</m> is a
      <term>limit</term><idx>limit of a sequence</idx> of <m>\vx</m>, if
      the sequence <m>\vx-r</m> is null. We denote this by
      <me>
        \lim x_n = r, \qquad x_n \to r, \qquad \text{or} \qquad \vx \approx r.
      </me>
      The last notation captures the idea that a convergent sequence can be
      viewed as an approximation to its limit.
    </p>

    <p>
      A sequence is <term>convergent</term> <idx>convergent sequence</idx>
      if it has a limit, otherwise it is <term>divergent</term><idx>divergent
      sequence</idx>. We also distinguish two common types of divergent
      behavior. We write <m>x_n \to +\infty</m> if for every
      <m>M \in \R</m> we have <m>x_n \gt M</m> for all sufficiently large
      <m>n</m>. Similarly, we write <m>x_n \to -\infty</m> if for every
      <m>M \in \R</m> we have <m>x_n \lt M</m> for all sufficiently large
      <m>n</m>.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-sequences-fundamental-results">
    <title>Fundamental Results</title>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-null-sequence-basic-operations">
      <statement>
	<p> Suppose <m>(x_n)</m> and <m>(y_n)</m> are null sequences. Then 

	</p> 
	<ol>
	   <li> <m>(x_n+y_n)</m> is null. </li>
	   
	   <li>
	        <m>(c_nx_n)</m> is null if <m>(c_n)</m> is bounded.
	   </li>	   
        </ol>
      </statement> 

      <proof>
	<p>
          For (1), let <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>. Choose <m>N_1,N_2</m> so that
          <m>|x_n| \lt \varepsilon/2</m> for all <m>n \ge N_1</m> and
          <m>|y_n| \lt \varepsilon/2</m> for all <m>n \ge N_2</m>. Then for
          <m>n \ge \max\{N_1,N_2\}</m>, the triangle inequality gives
          <m>|x_n+y_n| \le |x_n|+|y_n| \lt \varepsilon</m>.
	</p>

	<p> For (2), by <xref ref="prop-bounded-iff-abs-bound"/> there exists <m>M \gt 0</m>
	such that <m>|c_n| \lt M</m> for every <m>n</m>. Let <m>\varepsilon
	\gt 0</m>, then for all <m>n \gg 0</m>, <m>|x_n| \lt \varepsilon</m>
	and hence <m>|c_n x_n| \lt M\varepsilon</m>. This shows that
	<m>(c_nx_n)</m> is a null sequence because <m>M\varepsilon</m>
	is an arbitrary positive number as <m>M \ge 0</m> and <m>\varepsilon
	\ge 0</m> is arbitrary.
     </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <p>
      The proof of (1) illustrates an important general point: if a statement
      <m>P</m> holds for all sufficiently large <m>n</m> and a statement
      <m>Q</m> also holds for all sufficiently large <m>n</m>, then the
      conjunction "<m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>" holds for all sufficiently large
      <m>n</m>.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-convergent-sequence-unique-limit">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A convergent sequence has a unique limit.
        </p>
      </statement> <proof>
	<p>
	  Suppose <m>x_n \to r</m> and <m>x_n \to r'</m>. Then both
	  <m>(r-x_n)</m> and <m>(x_n-r')</m> are null sequences. By <xref
	  ref="prop-null-sequence-basic-operations"/>, their sum
	  <m>(r-r')</m> is also null. A constant sequence is null only if its
	  constant value is zero, so <m>r-r'=0</m>. Therefore <m>r=r'</m>.
	</p> </proof>
    </proposition>


    <proposition xml:id="prop-convergent-sequence-bounded">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every convergent sequence is bounded.
        </p>
      </statement> <proof>
	<p>
	  Suppose <m>x_n \to r</m>. Then there exists <m>N</m> such that
	  <m>|x_n-r| \lt 1</m> for all <m>n \ge N</m>. Hence <m>|x_n|
	  \le |x_n-r|+|r| \lt 1+|r|</m> for all <m>n \ge N</m>. It follows
	  that <me>
	    |x_n| \le \max\{|x_1|,\ldots,|x_N|,1+|r|\}
	  </me> for every <m>n</m>. Thus <m>(x_n)</m> is bounded.
	</p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <p>
	The proof above shows that "eventually bounded" and "bounded" are
	the same for sequences.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-monotone-convergence">
      <title>Monotone Convergence Theorem</title> <statement>
	<p>
          Every bounded monotone sequence converges.
        </p>
      </statement> 

      <proof>
	<p>
          First suppose <m>(x_n)</m> is increasing and bounded. Then its set of
          terms <m>S:=\{x_n \colon n \in \N\}</m> is nonempty and bounded above,
          so <m>s:=\sup S</m> exists.
        </p>

        <p>
	  Let <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>. Since <m>s-\varepsilon</m> is not an
	  upper bound of <m>S</m>, there exists <m>N</m> such that
          <m>s-\varepsilon \lt x_N \le s</m>. As <m>(x_n)</m> is increasing, for
          every <m>n \ge N</m> we have
	  <me>
	    s-\varepsilon \lt x_N \le x_n \le s \lt s+\varepsilon.
	  </me>
          Hence <m>|x_n-s| \lt \varepsilon</m> for all <m>n \ge N</m>, so
          <m>x_n \to s</m>.
	</p>

        <p>
          If <m>(x_n)</m> is decreasing and bounded, then <m>(-x_n)</m> is
          increasing and bounded. By the increasing case, <m>(-x_n)</m>
          converges, and then <xref ref="prop-limit-laws-sequences"/> implies
          that <m>(x_n)</m> converges as well.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      The next proposition shows that the usual algebraic operations on
      convergent sequences again produce convergent sequences, and that
      taking limits commutes with these operations.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-limit-laws-sequences">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>x_n \to x</m> and <m>y_n \to y</m>. Then:
	</p> <ol>
	  <li><m>x_n+y_n \to x+y</m>,</li>
          
	  <li><m>x_ny_n \to xy</m>,</li>

          <li><m>1/y_n \to 1/y</m>, provided <m>y \ne 0</m>.</li>
        
	</ol>
      </statement> 
      <proof> 

      <p>
        Both <m>(x_n-x)</m> and <m>(y_n-y)</m> are null, so
        <xref ref="prop-null-sequence-basic-operations"/> shows that their sum
        <m>(x_n-x)+(y_n-y)=(x_n+y_n)-(x+y)</m> is null. Therefore
        <m>x_n+y_n \to x+y</m>.
      </p>

	<p>
	  Also
          <m>x_ny_n-xy = x_n(y_n-y) + (x_n-x)y</m>. By
          <xref ref="prop-convergent-sequence-bounded"/>, the sequence
          <m>(x_n)</m> is bounded. Hence
          <xref ref="prop-null-sequence-basic-operations"/> implies that
          <m>(x_n(y_n-y))</m> is null. Since the constant sequence <m>y</m> is
          bounded, the same proposition shows that <m>((x_n-x)y)</m> is null.
          Therefore <m>(x_ny_n-xy)</m> is null, and so <m>x_ny_n \to xy</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
          For the reciprocal, assume <m>y \neq 0</m>. Since <m>y_n \to y</m>,
          there exists <m>N</m> such that <m>|y_n-y| \lt |y|/2</m> for all
          <m>n \ge N</m>. For such <m>n</m>,
          <m>|y_n| \ge |y|-|y_n-y| \gt |y|/2</m>, so in particular
          <m>y_n \neq 0</m>. Moreover, for all <m>n \ge N</m>,
	
	<me>
	\left| \frac{1}{y_n} - \frac{1}{y}\right| =
	\left|\frac{y-y_n}{y y_n}\right| \le \frac{2|y_n-y|}{|y|^2}.
	</me>
	  
	Since <m>(y_n-y)</m> is null and <m>2/|y|^2</m> is a fixed number,
	<xref ref="prop-null-sequence-basic-operations"/> implies that
          <m>(1/y_n - 1/y)</m> is null. Thus <m>1/y_n \to 1/y</m>.
	</p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-squeeze-lemma">
      <title>Squeeze Lemma</title> <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>x_n \le z_n \le y_n</m> for every <m>n</m>, and suppose
          <m>x_n \to r</m> and <m>y_n \to r</m>. Then <m>z_n \to r</m>.
        </p>
      </statement> 

      <proof>
	<p>
          Let <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>. Since <m>x_n \to r</m> and <m>y_n \to r</m>,
          we have
          <m>|x_n-r| \lt \varepsilon</m> and <m>|y_n-r| \lt \varepsilon</m>
          for all sufficiently large <m>n</m>. For such <m>n</m>,
          <me>
            -\varepsilon \lt x_n-r \le z_n-r \le y_n-r \lt \varepsilon.
          </me>
          Hence <m>|z_n-r| \lt \varepsilon</m> for all sufficiently large
          <m>n</m>, so <m>z_n \to r</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-limit-preserves-nonnegativity">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>x_n \to r</m> and <m>x_n \ge 0</m> for every <m>n</m>, then
          <m>r \ge 0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement> 

      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose instead that <m>r \lt 0</m>. Then for all <m>n \gg 0</m>,
          <m>x_n-r \ge -r = |r|</m>, so <m>|x_n-r|\ge |r| \gt 0</m>. This
          contradicts <m>x_n \to r</m>. Therefore <m>r \ge 0</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <corollary xml:id="cor-limit-preserves-order">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>x_n \to x</m>, <m>y_n \to y</m>, and <m>x_n \le y_n</m> for
          every <m>n</m>, then <m>x\le y</m>.
        </p>
      </statement> <proof>
        <p>
          The sequence <m>(y_n - x_n)</m> converges to <m>y-x</m>
          by <xref ref="prop-limit-laws-sequences"/>, and each
          term is nonnegative. Hence <m>y-x \ge 0</m> by <xref
          ref="prop-limit-preserves-nonnegativity"/>, so <m>x \le y</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>

    <p>
      A <term>subsequence</term><idx>subsequence</idx> of a sequence
      <m>(x_n)</m> is a sequence of the form <m>(x_{n_k})</m>, where
      <m>(n_k)</m> is a strictly increasing sequence of natural numbers. In
      other words, a subsequence of <m>(x_n)</m> is a sequence of the form
      <m>(x_{\sigma(n)})</m>, where <m>\sigma</m> is a strictly increasing
      function from <m>\N</m> to itself.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-subsequence-of-convergent-sequence">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every subsequence of a convergent sequence converges to the
          same limit.
        </p>
      </statement> 

      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>x_n \to L</m> and <m>(x_{n_k})</m> is a subsequence.
          Since <m>(n_k)</m> is strictly increasing, we have <m>n_k \ge k</m>
          for every <m>k</m>.
        </p>

	<p>
	  Let <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>. Choose <m>N</m> such that
	  <m>|x_n-L| \lt \varepsilon</m> for all <m>n \ge N</m>. If
          <m>k \ge N</m>, then <m>n_k \ge k \ge N</m>, so
	  <m>|x_{n_k}-L| \lt \varepsilon</m>. Hence <m>x_{n_k} \to L</m>.
	</p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
  </subsection>
</section>
